<Author>LM79
<Content>Great location and friendly staff Let鈥檚 start with the location. The hotel is beside the Paral.lel metro station. You step off the metro and (so long as you take the Sant Pau exit) the hotel is immediately on your left, a welcome air conditioned haven after the heat of the underground. Paral.lel is one stop from the bottom of the Ramblas and Port Vell, the sea front shopping and dining area. You can easily walk to the Ramblas or the sea in 15 minutes (though the metro is so easy, you might as well save your feet!) Paral.lel is also the station which takes you up Montjuc and deposits you at the cable car station up to the castle. So, location wise, this hotel is spot on. The staff are very friendly and fluent in English. The hotel itself is very clean, simple and smart. It hasn't got boutique charm or 5* opulence, but wood panelling and muted mushroom colours make the hotel feel modern and sophisticated. Our room was average size with wooden floor and a window the size of one full wall. It was lovely. The bathroom was as you'd expect - clean and well appointed. The towel rail came in very handy for drying wet clothes overnight. They provide a bathroom kit in case you forget anything 鈥?so razor, toothbrush and paste etc. However, there are supermarkets near the hotel, so you鈥檒l be able to buy anything you鈥檝e forgotten. Our only complaints about the hotel were:- The housekeeping. We found the housekeeper was a bit forgetful! - The beds. A little hard.- The water. Tap water is heavily chlorinated and not drinkable. So you need to buy bottled. (There is a 24 hour supermarket just round the corner from the hotel that sells big bottles for 0.60 euros)- No kettle in the room.But these are MINOR complaints. Overall we enjoyed our stay and would definitely go back.TIPSVEGGIE FOOD鈥?is hard to get in Barcelona. A great place that had fantastic veggie options is Rita Blue. If you leave the main Rambla on Hospital Street and walk a few hundred yards, you'll see a church set back from the road to your left, and a small square. Rita Blue is on that square, serving delicious, reasonably priced food in a colourful welcoming venue. I had hummus and vegetables to start, followed by fritters of beef tomato and feta cheese. Amazing! Plus, they do great cocktails.A NICE CUPPA TEA鈥?It can be thirsty work walking around Barcelona all day, and a cuppa at the end of it would be very welcome. If you do like your tea, make sure you take a travel kettle, an adapter plug, tea bags and buy bottled water to boil. However, there is a nice (if basic) caf茅 near the hotel that does great tea. Leave the hotel and turn left and it is (I think) the third caf茅 on the street. It looks like a greasy spoon / diner. TRAVELLING鈥?Save your feet and buy a metro ticket for the duration of your stay. Everywhere you need to see will be close to a metro stop, and it is clean, easy to navigate and feels very safe. However, there are A LOT of stairs, so it may be a problem for people with limited mobility or users of wheelchairs. MONTJUC鈥?Too much to see, too few signs. We got really lost! What looks like a five minute walk on the map took us almost an hour. We literally wasted half a day up there just trying to get around on foot. So take the tourist bus to take it all in quickly and painlessly. VISITING IN SEPTEMBER鈥?We arrived during the annual Merce festival, which meant free music concerts throughout the city, parades, street entertainment, loads of firework displays. I really recommend it! PAVEMENTS鈥?We had a lot of rain when we were in Barcelona and it was very slippy underfoot as the pavements are all smooth concrete. I took a proper tumble, so be careful! 
