<Author>Gotham1
<Content>Great hotel We just returned from a family vacation in Spain. This is a pretty nice hotel and we enjoyed our stay here. The rooms are contemporary  modern  well appointed. The beds are a bit firm for me  the pillows a bit flat, but we found that true in other Spain hotels. The baths are well stocked, except for kleenex; towells are big and soft. The pool is small  cold  only open until 8. There isn't alot of deck area or chairs around the pool, but towells are provided and it makes for some nice relaxing after a long day of walking, if you can find a seat. The location is great. It is on a main street and easy acces to taxis and a metro stop in front of hotel. The staff seem to speak some english and are helpful for the most part. We did have trouble getting change one day and were told they couldn't give us change for a 10 euro. Skip the breakfast. It is 13 euro and not very extensive from an American point of veiw for a buffet. You can walk down the street and find a few places on the same block that serve breakfast for around 9 euro. If you are staying with kids, be forewarned that there is a sex shop down the street and a burlesque shop around the corner on the street to Las Rambles. Also, a street off of the street to Las Rambles is a hooker street. We were traveling with teenage boys, so it wasn't a problem for us. If you have to do laundry, there is a laundry on the block behind the hotel and one down the street to Las Rambles. Get there early, all the kids staying in hostals show up mid morning to do there laundry while they eat their breakfast of beer and sandwiches. There was also a problem with our reservation. I had reserved through Secrotel site online and the rate was different than the one the hotel had. They attributed it to the exchange rate, but I'm not sure. Try to make your reservation directly with the hotel. Our stay there was pleasant  Barcelona is a great place to see. Two good places to eat are La Galina down by the peir, pricey, but good; and The Attic on Las Rambles, gourmet food at a reasonable price. Don't miss the cathedral, La Sagrada Familia, parq Guell, MNAC, Montjuic (castle and Olympic area), Picasso museum, Tibidabo mountain, and the beach. The beach is crowded, topless, and water is cold with a lot of debris, but why go all the way there and not go to the beach. 
