<Content>Excellent location We have just returned from 4 days staying at the Universal Barcelona for my 30th Birthday...and i have to say we had a wonderfull time!Few little hints and tips to hopefully help your trip alongHOTELThe Hotel was very clean and comfortable. It is very much a business hotel and does'nt have very much character about it, but your not there for the hotel.Check in was very smooth...we were allocated a room on the fith floor ..but when we got there it had two single beds pushed together! I wasnt completly happy about this and we asked to move. Within 5 mins they had us and our luggage moved to a room out the back on the fourth floor, which was absolutly perfect. Good sized room and very clean. On our 3rd day we woke up and the bathroom lights were not working, so we called down and someone came to look within 2 mins. They could not fix the problem and told us we would have to move...which was a bit of a pain!!!!!! Anyhow, new room (suite) on the seventh floor at the front of the building, bit bigger with a sofa and extra sink in bathroom. We were kept awake all night long with the noise of the traffic and sirens which seemed like every 5 mins.Personally if we went back again i would definatley request a room out the back as it was much much quieter.FOODWe paid for Bed and Breakfast, so ate there every morning. Food wasnt that great to be honest and if i had the choice i would rather eat elsewhere at half the price.LOCATIONFANTASTIC!!!!!! The Metro Stop Parel-el is right outside the hotel, use this to get around the city, its cheap and clean. Just like the london underground its all colour coded so really easy to find your way around. Different ticket types so just get what you need for how many days you are there for. We actually walked loads and loads and Barcelona is very compact you can get around very easily on foot.We took taxis in the evenings to the restaurants which were very fairly priced too.We also Paid for 2 days on the open top tourist bus (22 Euros each) . Not really worth the price, it was absolutly packed at whatever stop you got on at, most people just sat on it the whole time and spent the rest of the time complaining they couldnt sit upstairs........ Walk around its much better fun :-)FOOD OUT AND ABOUTWell i have to say this was the biggest dissapointment for us.....Anywhere on the main tourist roads were masssivly overpriced and not much cop. Our first day we stopped in one of the many Tapas Bars on La Rambla , had 2 beers each and some tapas and it was 62 EUROS......We were completly in shock!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!! Your looking at about 5 euros for a beer......however wonder off a couple of blocks from the main streets and you will pay about 2 euros and the food was much better.Most of the restaurants at Port Olympic seemed to be about 30 euros a head for 3 courses....If you are a football fan FC Barcelona Nou Camp is worth a visit......My boyfriend was in his element and loved every minute of it :-) Try and get there early in the morning 9-30 - 10 ish as when we came out at 12 ish it was packed out!!!!!!!Overall, I had never been to Barcelona before and i had a wonderfull time...all the hustle and bustle of city life with the beach 10 mins walk from Christoper Columbus Column.....Have a fab time...we did :-)x 
